    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "The complete plastome of Houttuynia cordata, an important medicinal and edible plant, was identified and sequenced in this study. The circular plastome is 160,217 bp in length and consists of a pair of inverted repeats (IRs 26,854 bp each), which is separated by a large single-copy region (LSC, 88,189 bp) and a small single-copy region (SSC, 18,320 bp). It encodes 132 genes, of which 114 are unique genes (80 protein-coding genes, 30 tRNAs, and 4 rRNAs). The phylogenetic analysis strongly reveals the sister group between H. cordata and the clade including Piper kadsura, Piper cenocladum, Saruma henryi, and Asarum sieboldii.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Abstract"
        },
